= El once de septiembre

The radio carries it all morning: Hawker Hunters over Santiago, La Moneda burning, and by afternoon the sentence that ends an epoch — Salvador Allende is dead in the palace, and with him the *vía pacífica*, the thesis that this continent would be allowed to vote its way to socialism.

Mexico's response is the paradox in full dress. The government of the dirty war breaks with the junta, throws open the embassy in Santiago, and lands planeloads of the hunted at the capital's airport, where the President greets them personally — poets, ministers, widows of the Chilean process, soon an entire exile university. There will be a Casa de Chile with state patronage; there will be Hortensia Bussi received like a head of state. Guerrero, meanwhile, remains Guerrero. The asylum is real. The dirty war is real. The Republic performs solidarity abroad with the same hand it uses for the other thing at home, and feels no strain.

For the left, Chile is a wound and a syllabus in one: the ortodoxos read it as proof the ballot was always a trap; the renovadores read it as proof the ballot needs armor — alliances, masses, nerve. Both are quoting the same corpses.

- @volcarse: Throw the Party into the solidarity apparatus — committees, housing, presses, the airport at all hours.
- @discreta: Solidarity in proportion. The exiles have a wealthy host already; the Party's centavos are needed at home.

